{"posts":[{"no":118582333,"now":"03\/27\/17(Mon)19:59:59","name":"Anonymous","sub":"\/pol\/&#039;s reading","com":"Today I&#039;d like to share some of the things in what I&#039;ve read, Carl Schmitt&#039;s &quot;The Concept of the political&quot;. In it, Schmitt attempts to establish and justifies what he believes to be the defining act of politic, the distinction between friend and enemy. In a context in which the West is infected by the virus of humanity, I found this reading particularly pertinent. Indeed, the whole idea of humanity lies precisely in the idea that all human beings are au fond the same, and that thus if they were to have proper understanding of their true interests and of their proper relationship toward one another, the very possibility of discord of will, and thus of conflict, of a friend, enemy distinction, would disappear.<br><br>Bruno Gulli states as such in the introductory section of his book &quot;Human and the Enemy: How ethic can rid politics of violence&quot;.<br><br><span class=\"quote\">&gt;However, it makes sense to think of the unity of politics and ethics as an alternative to a world that seems unable or unwilling to deliver conditions of social justice and the good life for all\u2014 where \u201cfor all\u201d means a humanity that has surpassed the friend-and-enemy impasse, having perhaps eliminated the very concept or possibility of the enemy.<\/span><br><br>Of course, in order to assume that humanity should ever be able to overcome the very possibility of enmities between different people, Gulli as to appeal to a notion of the &quot;good life&quot; which I suspect many people would reject, to the point where they would be ready to define Gulli and his ilk as an enemy in the political sense.","filename":"2dc11cb20d910fe05b70de4c5c45c994","ext":".jpg","w":3083,"h":4001,"tn_w":192,"tn_h":250,"tim":1490659199738,"time":1490659199,"md5":"x2eev4qpckiEiNXcZlymjA==","fsize":3034232,"resto":0,"id":"0hUcfvwW","country":"CA","m_img":1,"bu