83954,"now":"03\/27\/17(Mon)20:13:34","name":"Anonymous","com":"<span class=\"quote\">&gt;In his endeavor to strengthen the Weimar state, Schmitt challenged a basic liberal assumption then widely held either for philosophical or tactical reasons, namely, that every political party, no matter how antirepublican, must be permitted freely to compete for parliamentary representation and for governmental power. This meant that the sole requirement of such parties in their quest for power was that they proceed legally.<\/span><br><br>Here we see -- again from the introduction by Tracy B. Strong -- what Schmitt was trying to achieve with his theory. Against a fundamentally procedural approach to politic, in which is tolerated what respects the established procedure, Shmitt seems to have wanted to argue that such an attitude consisted in the negation of the very possibility of an enemy hell bent on destroying one&#039;s way of life. Against such an attitude, Schmitt assert his view of the political as the ability to reject, and to do so violently. I would like to contrast this with Popper&#039;s &quot;paradox of tolerance.&quot;<br><br><span class=\"quote\">&gt;Less well known is the paradox of tolerance: Unlimited tolerance must lead to the disappearance of tolerance. If we extend unlimited tolerance even to those who are intolerant, if we are not prepared to defend a tolerant society against the onslaught of the intolerant, then the tolerant will be destroyed, and tolerance with them.<\/span><br><br><span class=\"quote\">&gt;The Open Society and Its Enemies Vol. 1.<\/span><br><br>Here we see, it seems, Popper agreeing in some sense with Schmitt. Every politi that affirms must also negate, and thus even those societies which wish to incarnate some idea of tolerance must never the less qualify it so as to reject these form of life which could destroy to very tolerance which they seek to achieve.","filename":"9f3b9e824cbd3b434898bac497f06e72","ext":".jpg","w":663,"h":944,"tn